issue.title: SECURITY FIX: Resolve XSS vulnerability in chat system - Fixes #140
issue.body:
# üîí Security Fix: XSS Vulnerability Resolution ## üö® **CRITICAL SECURITY FIX** This PR addresses a **high-severity XSS vulnerability** in the AgriTech chat system that allowed malicious script injection attacks. ## üìã **Issue Summary** **Issue:** #140 - Unsanitized innerHTML Usage in chat.js & chat.html **Type:** Security (XSS) **Severity:** High **Status:** ‚úÖ FIXED ### **Vulnerability Details** - **Root Cause:** Chat messages rendered via `element.innerHTML = messageContent` without HTML escaping - **Impact:** Cross-site scripting (XSS) allowing script injection and session hijacking - **Reproduction:** Send `` in chat input ## üõ†Ô∏è **Fixes Implemented** ### 1. **Client-Side Security (chat.js)** ```javascript // ‚úÖ ADDED: HTML escaping function function escapeHtml(text) { return text .replace(/&/g, '&') .replace(//g, '>') .replace(/"/g, '"') .replace(/'/g, '''); } // ‚úÖ REPLACED: Vulnerable innerHTML usage // Before: div.innerHTML = `
${format(txt)}
` // After: textDiv.innerHTML = format(escapeHtml(messageContent)) // ‚úÖ ADDED: Input validation if (input.length > 1000) { alert('Message too long. Please keep messages under 1000 characters.'); return; } ``` ### 2. **Content Security Policy (chat.html)** ```html ``` ### 3. **Server-Side Protection (app.py)** ```python # ‚úÖ ADDED: Input sanitization functions def sanitize_input(text): """Sanitize user input to prevent XSS and injection attacks""" if not text or not isinstance(text, str): return "" # Remove HTML tags text = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '', text) # Escape special characters text = text.replace('&', '&') text = text.replace('<', '<') text = text.replace('>', '>') text = text.replace('"', '"') text = text.replace("'", ''') # Limit length if len(text) > 1000: text = text[:1000] return text.strip() # ‚úÖ ADDED: Input validation def validate_input(data): """Validate input data structure and content""" if not data: return False, "No data provided" return True, "Valid input" ``` ## üß™ **Testing** ### **Attack Vectors Tested & Blocked:** - ‚úÖ `` - Script tag injection - ‚úÖ `` - Event handler injection - ‚úÖ `<script>alert('XSS')</script>` - HTML entity attacks - ‚úÖ Normal text messages - Functionality preserved ### **Security Verification:** - ‚úÖ All malicious scripts are displayed as text (not executed) - ‚úÖ Event handlers are properly escaped - ‚úÖ HTML entities are safely handled - ‚úÖ Normal chat functionality remains intact - ‚úÖ Markdown formatting still works correctly ## üìÅ **Files Modified** | File | Changes | Security Impact | |------|---------|----------------| | `chat.js` | Added HTML escaping, secure DOM manipulation, input validation | üîí **CRITICAL** | | `chat.html` | Added Content Security Policy header | üîí **HIGH** | | `app.py` | Added input sanitization and validation functions | üîí **MEDIUM** | | `SECURITY_FIXES.md` | Added comprehensive security documentation | üìö **DOCS** | ## üîç **Before vs After Comparison** ### **Before (Vulnerable):** ```javascript // ‚ùå VULNERABLE CODE div.innerHTML = `
${name}
${format(txt)}
${time}
`; ``` **Result:** User input `` would execute JavaScript ### **After (Secure):** ```javascript // ‚úÖ SECURE CODE function displayMessage(messageContent, sender) { const messageElement = document.createElement('div'); // ... safe DOM creation textDiv.innerHTML = format(escapeHtml(messageContent)); } ``` **Result:** User input `` becomes `<script>alert('XSS')</script>` (displayed as text) ## üéØ **Security Benefits** - **üîí XSS Prevention:** All script injection attacks blocked - **üõ°Ô∏è Input Validation:** Message length limits and structure validation - **üîê CSP Protection:** Restricts unauthorized script execution - **üßπ Sanitization:** Server-side HTML tag removal and character escaping - **üìù Documentation:** Comprehensive security guidelines ## ‚úÖ **Verification Checklist** - [x] XSS vulnerability eliminated - [x] Normal chat functionality preserved - [x] Input validation implemented - [x] Content Security Policy added - [x] Server-side sanitization added - [x] Security documentation updated - [x] All attack vectors tested and blocked ## üöÄ **Deployment Notes** - **No breaking changes** - All existing functionality preserved - **Backward compatible** - No database migrations required - **Performance impact** - Minimal (only adds HTML escaping) - **User experience** - No visible changes to end users **‚ö†Ô∏è IMPORTANT:** This is a **critical security fix** that should be deployed immediately to prevent potential XSS attacks. **üîç Reviewers:** Please focus on security implications and verify that all attack vectors are properly blocked.

Add cursor based pagination and remove count(*)

SQL count(*) can be very time expensive on large databases.
In most cases, clients do not care about know the total
number of rows and fetch page by page.
Therefore, removing the total count from the result will make
queries faster.

In addition, cursor based pagination guarantees that when fetching
an entire collection, there will be no duplicated elements in
consecutive pages.

pull_request.title: Add foreach target expansion and value-level Jinja rendering
pull_request.body:
## Summary
- parse manifests as plain YAML before templating
- add `foreach`/`when` expansion and render Jinja only in value fields
- document YAML-first pipeline and mark roadmap item as complete

## Testing
- `make fmt`
- `make check-fmt`
- `make lint`
- `make test`
- `make markdownlint`
- `make nixie` *(fails: Error running command bun x --bun @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli ...)*

------
https://chatgpt.com/codex/tasks/task_e_689fd546e328832294c3173c362fb38c

## Summary by Sourcery

Parse manifests as YAML before templating, implement `foreach`/`when` target expansion, and restrict Jinja evaluation to value-level string fields.

New Features:
- Add `foreach` and `when` keys to generate targets dynamically with `item` and `index` variables.
- Enable Jinja rendering only within string values after deserialization.

Enhancements:
- Refactor manifest parsing pipeline to perform YAML parsing first, then expand `foreach`, then render templated values.
- Update examples and AST handling to accommodate YAML-first and value-level rendering.

Documentation:
- Revise design documentation to describe the three-stage YAML-first pipeline and remove the legacy two-pass mechanism.
- Mark related roadmap items as complete.

Tests:
- Add and update tests for `foreach` expansion, `when` filtering, and related error cases in parsing.

Chores:
- Update example manifest files to new `foreach` syntax.

release.name: CitadelQuest v0.4.19-alpha
release.body:
CitadelQuest v0.4.19-alpha Release

This release includes:

### Major AI Toolbox Enhancement
- **Comprehensive File Management AI Tools**: New tools for Spirits including listFiles, getFileContent, createDirectory, updateFileEfficient, getProjectTree, manageFile
- **AI Tool Self-Management**: listAITools and setAIToolActive tools allow Spirits to manage their own capabilities
- **Meta-Tool Management Service**: AIToolToolService enables Spirits to control their toolset with safety checks
- **Smart Tool Defaults**: Migration with intelligent active/inactive defaults for optimal user experience

### Spirit Chat System Improvements
- Enhanced API service and manager components for better performance
- Improved UI styling and responsiveness
- Better conversation flow and user experience
- Enhanced frontend-backend integration

### Service Architecture Updates
- Enhanced AIToolCallService with new tool integrations
- Improved file service capabilities with advanced operations
- Better gateway service implementations
- Updated service container configuration for optimal dependency injection

### Internationalization Expansion
- Complete translations for all new AI tools (English, Czech, Slovak)
- Enhanced user settings and AI configuration pages
- Improved Spirit Chat interface translations
- Comprehensive language support for new features

### Documentation Updates
- Updated README with comprehensive project overview
- Enhanced setup instructions and feature descriptions
- Improved development guidelines and architecture documentation

### Update
1. Visit the auto-update page on your CitadelQuest installation: `/admin/update/check`

### Installation
1. Download the Installation Package (`citadelquest-installer-v0.4.19-alpha.zip`)
2. Upload `install.php` to your web server (in directory: `/public`, next to `index.php/html`)
3. Access `install.php` through your web browser
4. The installer will automatically:
   - Check environment requirements
   - Download and extract the pre-built package
   - Set up the database
   - Configure permissions

### Release Packages

1. **Pre-built Package** (Release A):
   - Full application with all dependencies
   - Pre-compiled assets + database
   - Size: 17MB

2. **Installation Package** (Release B):
   - Lightweight zero-configuration & zero-click installer
   - Downloads and sets up the pre-built package
   - Size: 5KB

issue.title: Support PodLevelResources

labels.name: kind/feature
labels.description: Categorizes issue or PR as related to a new feature.

issue.body:
<!-- Please only use this template for submitting enhancement requests -->

**What would you like to be added**:
It would be great if we can support [the PodLevelResources feature](https://github.com/kubernetes/enhancements/blob/master/keps/sig-node/2837-pod-level-resource-spec/kep.yaml). Indeed, this feature is still alpha stage, but the APIs has already been added to k/k corev1 API.

Indeed, we have already started to use the [`PodRequests`](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/69ab91a5c59617872c9f48737c64409a9dec2957/staging/src/k8s.io/component-helpers/resource/helpers.go#L120) helper to calculate total Pod resources in https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kueue/pull/4177, which means we can calculate the requested Pod resources with PodLevelResources by passing something to the `PodResourceOptions`.

Once we have done the below tasks, we can confirm the PodLevelResources compatibility with Kueue.

- [ ] Add Unit / Integration testings by using Pod with `.spec.resources` (‚â† `.spec.containers.resources`)
- [ ] Refine the total Pod resources calculation mechanism to support `.spec.resources` in the following:
    - https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kueue/blob/2738e8b05c03fe5dcf38beba1f4769fe2e1888c9/pkg/cache/tas_flavor.go
    - https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kueue/blob/main/pkg/util/limitrange/limitrange.go
    - https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/kueue/blob/main/pkg/workload/workload.go

> [!NOTE]
> We need to enable Kubernetes featureGate, `PodLevelResources` in kube-scheduler, kube-apiseerver, and kubelet to verify the behavior.

**Why is this needed**:
It would be better to support k/k new enhancements.

**Completion requirements**:

This enhancement requires the following artifacts:

- [ ] Design doc
- [ ] API change
- [x] Docs update

The artifacts should be linked in subsequent comments.

issue.body:
If you haven‚Äôt already, check out our [contributing guidelines](https://github.com/Expensify/ReactNativeChat/blob/main/contributingGuides/CONTRIBUTING.md) for onboarding and email contributors@expensify.com to request to join our Slack channel!
___

**Version Number:** 9.1.95-1
**Reproducible in staging?:** Yes
**Reproducible in production?:** Yes
**If this was caught during regression testing, add the test name, ID and link from TestRail:** https://test-management.browserstack.com/projects/2219752/test-runs/TR-286/folder/13176670/41237099/842122512
**Email or phone of affected tester (no customers):** ibellicotest+1606@gmail.com
**Issue reported by:** Applause Internal Team
**Device used:** Motorola MotoG60 / Android 12 / Chrome ( mWeb / Hybrid app) - Windows 10 / Chrome
**App Component:** Money Requests

## Action Performed:
Prerequisite: Account has at least one workspace available.
Prerequisite 2: Account has a Self DM.
1. Open the staging.new.expensify.com website.
2. Open any workspace chat.
3. Create a manual expense.
4. Create a new report on the same workspace chat, but don¬¥t submit any expense to it.
5. Open the expense created on step 3.
6. Tap on the report field and select the report created on step 4.
7. Once expense is moved and you land on the empty report, tap on "More" and delete the report.
8. Open the report where the expense was moved.
9. Note that a "Moved this expense to your personal space" system message is displayed.

## Expected Result:
When an expense is moved to a different report on the same workspace, the system message generated with this action, should be "Moved this expense to Expense Report XX".

## Actual Result:
When an expense is moved to a different report on the same workspace, and the first report is deleted, the correct "Moved this expense to Expense Report XX" appears, but also a "Moved this expense to your personal space" message can be seen on the moved expense.
